Movements, Home range and Social organization.
The Great Basin Pocket Mouse appears to be asocial. In paired encounters in the laboratory, it was agonistic and dominant over kangaroo mice (
Microdipodops
), the Little Pocket Mouse (
P. longimembris
), and the North American Deermouse (Peromyscus maniculatus). Estimates of home ranges vary widely (0-01-4 ha), but male home ranges appear to be larger than those of females. Studies disagree on the extent of overlapping of home ranges. Estimates of density average 28-5 ind/ha, but it may be greater than 80 ind/ha during years with precipitation is above average. The Great Basin Pocket Mouse frequently is numerically dominant in small mammal communities of the Great Basin.
